👉Nutrition & Gut Healing Tips:

✅Start your day with soaked nuts & seeds (especially flax, pumpkin, and walnut) for hormonal support.

✅Avoid whey protein , eggs & switch to food protein like moong chilla, tofu, or soaked dals (in moderation).

✅No raw veggies with thyroid issues — lightly cook or steam cruciferous ones.

✅Include fermented foods daily: kanji, sauerkraut, or homemade curd 

✅Cut out processed sugars completely — acne and insulin resistance will thank you.

✅Rotate dals and legumes weekly to avoid overloading the gut.

✅Have jeera-saunf-ajwain water post lunch and dinner to ease bloating.

✅Eat within a 10–11 hour window (circadian fasting helps with hormones + weight loss).

👉Lifestyle & Stress Tips:

✅Sleep by 10–10:30 pm max — most hormonal repair happens before midnight.

✅Avoid scrolling at night — blue light = cortisol spikes = belly fat.

✅Don’t work out hard during your period — listen to your body, do stretching/yoga.

👉Exercise & Movement Tip:

✅3–4 days strength training (even bodyweight or ZUMBA ) = essential for thyroid + metabolism.

👉Mindset & Habits Tips:

✅Don’t obsess over the scale — track inches, mood, skin, and energy.

✅Plan 1 free meal a week guilt-free — it helps sustainability.

✅Batch-cook 2–3 go-to meals (millet upma, egg curry, veg soup) to avoid ordering junk.

✅Hydrate with electrolytes if on low-carb — especially with thyroid imbalance.

✅Celebrate small wins weekly — consistency matters more than perfection.

I toh only eat Multigrain Atta and give to my family also - this is what my client told me . I was surprised and told her that this isn’t a healthy habit and asked her to do as below: ( I hope you are also not making the same mistake of mixing all grains together ) 

If you have gut issues like bloating, indigestion, or low appetite, I don’t recommend multigrain atta.
Here’s why 👇

🔍 Each grain has a different digestion time and needs specific enzymes to break down.
When you mix 4–5 grains in one flour, it can confuse your digestive system and lead to poor absorption, gas, and heaviness.

✅ Instead, eat single-grain atta as per the season.
This is what I suggest:

🌧️ Monsoon – Ragi or Besan
Why? These are light, drying grains that help manage excess moisture in the body.
Ragi is rich in calcium and good for bones + digestion. Besan supports gut balance and doesn’t feel heavy.

❄️ Winter – Bajra, Jowar, or Makka
These are warming grains that generate internal heat and support metabolism.
Bajra is high in fiber and iron, great for energy. Makka supports bone health. Jowar is gluten-free and easy to digest.

☀️ Summer – Barley or Rice
These are cooling grains that help manage body heat and acidity.
Barley improves hydration and gut lining. Rice is light, soothing, and calming on the stomach.

📌 Seasonal eating isn't just tradition — it’s science.
Eating grains that align with the weather helps your body digest better, absorb more, and stay in balance.

If you’re dealing with digestive issues, try switching to single-grain, seasonal flours for a few weeks — and observe the change 🌿

🌿 Cortisol & Stress-Balancing Mulethi Tulsi Tea 🌿

One of the cheapest yet most powerful herbal blends to calm your nervous system 💆‍♀️🧘‍♂️

✨ Ingredients:
▫️ 1 small piece of mulethi bark (about 1 inch)
▫️ 5–7 fresh tulsi leaves (or 1 tsp dried)
▫️ 1.5 cups water

Optional:
▫️ A few fennel seeds or 1 crushed cardamom (for digestion + taste)
▫️ ½ tsp raw honey (add only once the tea has slightly cooled)

🍵 Method:
1️⃣ Add water, mulethi & tulsi to a pan
2️⃣ Boil for 7–8 mins on medium flame
3️⃣ Simmer for another 2–3 mins until slightly reduced
4️⃣ Strain into a cup
5️⃣ Let it cool a bit & add honey if desired

⏰ Best time to drink:
Mid-morning or evening (not on a full stomach)

latestPosts.caption:
Ghee, rice, roti — sabko villain bana diya gaya 😔 But they’re NOT the problem.
The real issue? Portion, timing, and your gut health.

❌ Why They've Become "Evil" in Popular Diet Culture:
🍽️ Portion Size Gone Wrong

It’s not the 1 roti with ghee that causes weight gain…

It’s 4 rotis + oil-heavy sabzi + no movement that overloads digestion.

🕒 Wrong Timing

Eating rice at 10 PM while lying on the couch isn’t the same as having it at 1 PM with dal and sabzi.

Late-night carbs = insulin spike + fat storage.

⚖️ Mindless Mixing

Eating all grains together (roti, rice, poha, upma in the same day) overwhelms digestion and raises blood sugar frequently.

🌍 Western Diet Culture Influence

“No carbs after 6” or “fat-free everything” made us believe that ghee and rice are “fattening.”

But Indian bodies thrive on seasonal grains and fats — if paired mindfully.

🥣 Lack of Gut Health Awareness

With a sluggish gut, even good food causes bloating.

So ghee or rice gets blamed, when the real issue is digestion, stress, and inflammation.

✅ The Truth:
-Ghee supports hormones
-Rice is easy to digest
-Roti offers complex carbs for energy

It's not about cutting them out. It’s about how you pair, portion, and time them.
